<section class="card">
  <h2>The basic method</h2>
  <p>
    The pages in this section use two different kinds of season signals: frost timing and heat accumulation.
    Frost dates estimate the outdoor window for tender crops. Growing degree days estimate whether the season is warm enough for a crop to mature inside that window.
  </p>
  <ol class="tight">
    <li><strong>Find the frost window.</strong> Last spring frost and first fall frost define the average outdoor season for tender crops.</li>
    <li><strong>Estimate seasonal heat.</strong> Growing degree days measure accumulated warmth, which matters for heat-loving crops.</li>
    <li><strong>Compare crops against the season.</strong> Crop heat requirements and maturity timing show which crops have room to finish and which are tight.</li>
    <li><strong>Account for timing pressure.</strong> A crop that works with perfect timing may become risky if it is planted one or two weeks late.</li>
  </ol>
</section>

